            <p class="blog-lead">
                Most email providers limit attachments to 10-25MB. A PDF with
                images or charts can easily exceed that. Here's how to shrink
                it without making it look terrible.
            </p>

            <h2>Why are PDFs so large?</h2>
            <p>
                PDFs get large for a few reasons. Images embedded in PDFs are
                often stored at print resolution (300dpi or higher) — far more
                than a screen needs to display clearly. Fonts can be embedded
                multiple times. And PDFs created from PowerPoint or Word often
                include unnecessary metadata and redundant objects.
            </p>
            <p>
                Compression targets all of these — downsampling images to
                screen resolution, removing redundant data, and optimizing
                the internal structure.
            </p>

            <h2>How much can you compress a PDF?</h2>
            <p>
                It depends heavily on the content. A PDF full of high-resolution
                photos can be compressed by 70-85%. A text-heavy PDF (like a
                contract or report) might only compress 20-40% since the text
                is already efficient. PDFs with charts and diagrams typically
                fall in the middle — 40-60% reduction.
            </p>

            <h2>Step-by-step: Compress a PDF for email</h2>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to <a href="/compress-pdf">PdfToolStack Compress PDF</a></li>
                <li>Upload your PDF (drag and drop or click to browse)</li>
                <li>Click <strong>Compress PDF</strong></li>
                <li>Download the compressed file</li>
                <li>Check the file size — it shows the reduction percentage</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                No signup required. Files are deleted within 1 hour.
                The whole process takes under 10 seconds.
            </p>

            <h2>Tips for best results</h2>
            <p>
                If your PDF is still too large after compression, try these:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Split the PDF</strong> — if it's a long document,
                    split it into sections and send separately using
                    <a href="/split-pdf">PDF Splitter</a>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Remove unnecessary pages</strong> — delete cover pages,
                    blank pages, or appendices that aren't needed using
                    <a href="/delete-pdf-pages">Delete PDF Pages</a>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Use a file sharing link instead</strong> — upload to
                    Google Drive or OneDrive and share a link rather than attaching
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Will compression affect text quality?</h2>
            <p>
                No — text in PDFs is stored as vector data, not as an image.
                Compression only affects raster images (photos, scans).
                Text will remain perfectly sharp at any zoom level after compression.
            </p>

            <h2>Common email attachment limits</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Gmail:</strong> 25MB per email</li>
                <li><strong>Outlook:</strong> 20MB per email</li>
                <li><strong>Yahoo Mail:</strong> 25MB per email</li>
                <li><strong>Apple Mail:</strong> Depends on your provider</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                If your compressed PDF is still over the limit, use Google Drive
                or Dropbox to share instead — most email clients will offer this
                automatically when your attachment is too large.
            </p>

